  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Childhood Regained: empowering communities to uphold children&apos;s rights (GHANA)</narrative>
  </title>
  <description>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">It is estimated that at least 7 out of 10 people in Northern Ghana live on less than US$2 dollars a day and are unable to meet basic needs including education and health. Chronic poverty has brought with it increasing evidence of hazardous child labour, including agricultural labour amongst boys and forced migration of girls to towns as porters and domestic workers, as well as sexual exploitation in their home communities. 

Building on the experience of previous Comic Relief funded work, this project aims to reduce hazardous child labour in four rural communities by helping children, through self-help clubs, to access education and to stay in school. Through women&#x2019;s groups, parents and other community adults will be assisted to access credit and skills. This will reduce dependence on their children&#x2019;s labour, as well as building their knowledge and understanding to protect their children better. Community-led advocacy with local leaders (such as teachers) will foster improvements in the governance and management of local schools. Longer term, the project aims to build a model of community driven child labour prevention which can be replicated in other rural communities.</narrative>
  </description>
